<FIRST>u a BC-ExxonValdez 2ndLd-Writethru a0625 07-30 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Exxon Valdez, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0625,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Damaged Oil Tanker Enters Bay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with details from scene. Picks
up 8th graf, `Solberg said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two tugboats pushed the damaged oil tanker
Exxon Valdez into San Diego Bay early Sunday for repairs of
ruptures that caused the nation's worst oil spill five months ago.
   The high-riding tanker, which was ringed by eight Coast Guard
and Harbor Patrol boats for security reasons, crawled along at 3
knots, about 3{ mph, under a gray sky.
   Dozens of pleasure boats sailed along outside the security zone,
and ships with salvage and pollution response gear trailed behind.
Boats carrying environmentalists also trailed, watching for any
signs of leakage.
   The Greenpeace organization deployed four sailboats and four
inflatable boats that carried banners stating, ``Oil Spills Kill,''
``Exxon Rules'' and ``Change The Course, Steer Toward Sane Energy.''
   Hundreds of people watched from the shoreline as the tanker
entered the bay and rounded North Island, sailing past waterfront
hotels and Navy warships. Harbor seals stared from resting spots
atop buoys.
   The long-delayed entry began after authorities said the tanker
cleared its final inspection and gave Exxon the go-ahead to bring
it in.
   The tanker, which spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil into
Alaska's Prince William Sound when it went aground on March 24, was
originally to enter under its own power but at the last moment
tugboats were ordered to push it.
   Coast Guard Lt. Larry Solberg and Tom Gillette, an Exxon
Shipping Co. official, said the switch to tugboats was at the
request of a state water quality control official who wanted the
ship to be under greater control.
   The seven-mile trip into the bay began about 6 a.m. when the
Exxon Valdez was under its own power, stalled for a time for the
tugs to move in, and then resumed.
   Solberg said a final inspection by remote-controlled underwater
camera verified that the 987-foot hull was free of dangling steel
plates like those that had prevented the tanker's entry to the
harbor for weeks.
   Gillette said the plan was to enter with the rising tide, which
peaks at 9:30 a.m. The ship's transit through the bay to the
National Steel and Shipbuilding Co. dock was expected to take
several hours.
   For the past three weeks, the ship has stayed about 50 miles
from San Diego after initially being turned away as a pollution
risk. Its original entry to the bay was halted when officials
spotted a slick coming from the vessel.
</TEXT>
