<FIRST>r i AM-China-Nuns     07-30 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Nuns,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing Catholic Church Inducts First Nuns Since 1949</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven young women Sunday became the first to take
vows as Catholic nuns in Beijing since the Communists took power in
1949.
   Hundreds of people crowded Beijing's Nantang Cathedral to watch
Bishop Fu Tieshan induct the women as sisters of the
state-sponsored Patriotic Catholic Church, which has no ties with
the Vatican.
   The seven bowed their heads, covered by long black veils topped
with circlets of plastic roses, as Fu admonished them to be true to
their religious training, which began in 1986.
   After the 90-minute service, the new nuns posed for photographs
with the bishop on the cathedral steps, then left for their new
life.
   ``I'm very excited,'' one said as she rushed to greet relatives
and friends. She said they would be assigned church work but that
she did not know what it would be.
   Only about 3 million of China's 1.2 billion people belong to the
Patriotic Catholic Church. Life has not been easy for them since
1949, nor for the unknown number of Catholics who still are loyal
to the Vatican and worship in illegal churches.
   Catholics and members of other religious groups repeatedly were
singled out as politically suspect during leftist campaigns in the
first decades of Communist rule, especially during the 1966-76
Cultural Revolution when all churches were closed.
   Churches, seminaries and convents began reopening over the past
decade, and training began for a new generation of priests and
nuns. Two elderly nuns who had taken vows before 1949 were given
the task of training Beijing's first new nuns.
   One of those who took vows Sunday, Sister Yang Lijun, 24, said
she and the others came from Catholic families. ``I wanted to be a
nun since I was small ... in order to serve people,'' she said.
   Churches in several other cities also began accepting candidates
to become nuns in the mid-1980s, but the official Xinhua News
Agency said in April that the group in Beijing would take its vows
first.
   Before being admitted for training as nuns or priests,
candidates are tested in political as well as religious knowledge,
and their classes include socialist theory.
</TEXT>
