<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-89 1346EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan Bjt   07-30 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan, Bjt,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says U.S. Holds Cards of Peace and War in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the Kabul government, the United
States holds the cards of war or peace when it meets the Soviet
Union on Monday to discuss Afghanistan.
   But much as the Soviet-backed government of President Najib
would like the Americans to play the peace card, it sees the war
card coming up. U.S. diplomats predict new military offensives, and
U.S.-supplied rockets pound Kabul every day.
   The meeting in Stockholm, Sweden, will be the first superpower
discussion focusing on the 10-year Afghan civil war since the last
Soviet troops left this central Asian nation Feb. 15.
   Najib has confounded Western diplomats who predicted Moslem
rebels would topple his Soviet-backed government within days of the
Soviet pullout. He remains in power while the guerrillas, who call
themselves mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors, appear to be
squabbling among themselves.
   So far, the mujahedeen have failed to win control of a major
city and have been driven back from the key city of Jalalabad, 45
miles from the Pakistan border.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani on Saturday
accused the mujahedeen of firing rockets at Kabul for the past
month to ``have something in their hand'' when the Stockholm talks
start. The long-range rockets have killed more than 200 people,
virtually all civilians.
   Six rockets hit the capital Sunday, damaging Kabul University,
destroying a factory, and killing two women, the government said.
   ``We want the U.S. to show us the peace card,'' Amani said.
``But the signals have indicated that the United States in the
Stockholm talks will be stressing a military solution.''
   Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil said the most important thing the
Americans and Soviets could do would be to encourage ``hostile
groups'' to start a dialogue. He also urged the superpowers to
discuss a comprehensive peace settlement.
   But Peter Tomsen, a special U.S. envoy to the mujahedeen
appointed by President Bush, has predicted a major guerrilla
offensive during the remaining fighting season, which lasts until
November snows. He told a U.S. congressional committee Thursday:
``The end is clear. The resistance will prevail.''
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan, which serves as the
base for the major guerrilla groups, also has predicted intensified
war.
   In this dusty capital surrounded by hills, many diplomats and
foreigners of all stripes have their doubts about a mujahedeen
victory.
   Many are also concerned that a mujahedeen-controlled government,
likely led by Islamic fundamentalists who have received the lion's
share of U.S. military aid, would turn Afghanistan into another
Iran.
   Wakil said the Afghan government has shown it can defend itself
and predicted U.S. pursuit of the military option will fail.
   U.S. officials have been quoted as saying the rebels will get
new weapons to counter highly effective high-altitude bombing
attacks by the Afghan air force and to crater runways of Afghan air
bases.
   The Soviets want an end to hostilities. But Soviet Ambassador
Yuli M. Vorontsov, also first deputy foreign minister, told a
Western correspondent here earlier this month that he was not
optimistic.
   ``The Americans have been telling us privately what they've been
saying publicly about the arms supplies to the mujahedeen.
Therefore, we don't expect much from the beginning of the talks,''
he said.
   Another sign of low expectations is the low level of the
delegations.
   The Soviet delegation will be led by Ambassador-at-large Nikolai
I. Kozyrev, a former diplomat in Afghanistan who participated in
negotiations on the U.N.-brokered agreement that led to the
departure of Soviet troops.
   The U.S. delegation will be led by John Kelly, assistant
secretary of state for near eastern and south Asian affairs.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking anonymously, said the most
important thing that has happened on the political front is the
Soviet recognition of the mujahedeen _ and their agreement to
include the rebels in a coalition government.
   The Afghan government stresses that Najib has offered free and
fair elections under international supervision with all parties
competing, and has pledged to step down if the mujahedeen win.
</TEXT>
