<FIRST>u i BC-Hostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0638 07-30 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hostages, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0638,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Extremists Threaten To Kill Higgins Unless Israel Frees Cleric</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE that no photo received, Iranian condemnation
of the Obeid kidnapping, pvs comments from Israel and Bush. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Shiite Moslem captors of U.S. Marine
Col. William R. Higgins threatened Sunday to hang him within 24
hours if Israel fails to free the pro-Iranian fundamentalist cleric
it abducted from Lebanon.
   ``This will be our first response to the stupid Israeli
aggression and the flagrant American support that proves U.S.
complicity in the crime,'' said a statement issued by the
underground Organization of the Oppressed on Earth.
   ``We shall carry out the death sentence handed down against
proven spy Higgins by hanging him at exactly 3 p.m. (8 a.m. EDT)
Monday if Sheik Abdul-Karim Obeid and his two brethren have not
been freed by then,'' said the typewritten Arabic statement.
   It was delivered to a Western news agency in Beirut two days
after helicopter-borne Israeli commandoes kidnapped Obeid, 33, and
two colleagues from Obeid's home in a southern Lebanese village and
flew them to Israel.
   The statement was not accompanied by a picture of Higgins, the
usual confirmation of authenticity. But the statement appeared to
have been typed on the same machine and the same paper as earlier
statements. Previous statements had photographs of Higgins or of
his military identification card.
   After the commando raid Friday, some speculated that Israel
would try to swap Obeid and his colleagues for Higgins or for three
Israeli soldiers believed to be held in Lebanon since 1986 by
Obeid's group or its affiliates.
   Obeid is reputed to be the spiritual guide of the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, in south Lebanon. Obeid has denied any
links to the group.
   Hezbollah is widely believed to be the umbrella for Shiite
extremist factions, including the Oppressed on Earth, that are
holding most of the 17 Western hostages in Lebanon. Nine of the
hostages are Americans.
   The late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini maintained that Iran's 1979
Islamic Revolution was carried out for the mostazafin, or oppressed.
   On Saturday, Israeli leaders dismissed criticism of the
abduction and said Obeid led a ``fanatical'' group that had
launched terrorist attacks on Israel.
   On Friday, President Bush said he could not condone the commando
raid and that he did not know if it would help efforts to free
Higgins.
   In Tehran on Sunday, Iranian Interior Minister Ali Akbar
Montashemi told reporters that Islamic groups worldwide will
retaliate against the United States and Israel for the abduction of
Obeid.
   The Oppressed on Earth group claimed responsibility for
abducting Higgins, a decorated Vietnam veteran, near south
Lebanon's port city of Tyre on Feb. 17, 1988. They charged he was a
spy for the CIA.
   Higgins, 44, of Danville, Ky., served as head of a 76-member
observer group attached to the U.N. peacekeeping force in south
Lebanon.
   In a statement issued Dec. 12, 1988, the Oppressed on Earth said
it sentenced Higgins to death after ``he had made full confessions
about his espionage activities.'' That statement said Higgins had
been handed ``to those responsible in the organization ... to
execute this just verdict.''
   Of the 17 Western hostages, the longest held is Terry A.
Anderson, 41, chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated
Press.
   He was kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
