<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-89 1244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PatientDumping     07-30 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Patient Dumping,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Judge Decides Against Doctor in First Patient-Dumping Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has ruled against a doctor who was
the first prosecuted under a federal law against ``patient
dumping.''
   Dr. Michael Burditt, who ordered an uninsured pregnant woman who
was about to give birth to be transferred to another hospital 160
miles away, faces a $20,000 fine, Donald P. Wilcox, attorney for
the Texas Medical Association, said Saturday.
   The patient dumping law, which was part of the Consolidated
Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1986, forbids hospitals to
turn away patients needing emergency care or who are in active
labor.
   Burditt, who was off-duty at the time, made the decision as
chief of the obstetrical department at DeTar Hospital in Victoria.
   The case arose when Rosa Rivera _ poor and about to give birth
to her sixth child _ showed up at DeTar Hospital late on the
afternoon of Dec. 5, 1986.
   When a nurse called Burditt and told him Mrs. Rivera's blood
pressure was 210 over 130, he said she ``sounds like more than I
can handle.'' The blood pressure reading was higher than any he had
seen in 12 years of delivering babies.
   Burditt ordered Mrs. Rivera to be taken to John Sealy Hospital
in Galveston, 160 miles away. But the nurse and her supervisor were
concerned about the federal law.
   After some heated words between the doctor and the nurses, Mrs.
Rivera left the hospital in an ambulance. She gave birth to a
healthy baby boy a half-hour later, in the ambulance by the side of
the road.
   DeTar, which nearly lost its eligibility for Medicare funding,
paid a $5,000 fine after an investigation by the Dallas regional
office of the Department of Health and Human Services.
   Burditt refused to pay a $25,000 fine assessed against him and
the Texas and American medical associations took his side.
   Wilcox said the Health and Human Services administrative law
judge, Charles E. Stratton, lowered the fine because of ``some
mitigating factors.''
   Since the incident, Burditt has improved the transfer network
system and has helped set up an obstetric clinic to make prenatal
care more accessible for indigent patients, Wilcox said.
   A woman who identified herself as Burditt's wife said he would
have no comment until Monday. She also said that he was no longer
the chief of the hospital's obstetrical department but still
practices there.
</TEXT>
