<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIMAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The marriage of John Saffelo and Clara
Deets went down the tubes in a happy way. The couple took the
matrimonial plunge at a water park.
   The bride wore a white one-piece bathing suit and a flowing veil
in the ceremony Saturday at the Raging Waters amusement park. The
groom sported black swim trunks with white piping, a back bow tie
and black and white cuffs _ but nothing else.
   Saffello, 23, and Ms. Deets, 20, said their ``I dos'' at the top
of a slide, then plunged together down the spiraling 100-foot
tunnels of ``The Bermuda Triangle'' attraction at the park in
southern California.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Welz, a 9{-year-old police dog that
helped officers make more than 1,000 arrests, has retired.
   Two dozen officers came to the German shepherd's retirement
party Wednesday at a pizza parlor. Welz got a plaque from the Los
Angeles Police Department's anti-gang unit, thanking him for
sniffing out a homicide suspect May 16 in what turned out to be his
last arrest.
   But the K-9 veteran seemed more interested in a piece of pizza
crust than in his award.
   Welz probably could have worked for another two years, but his
handler, Sgt. John W. Bell, is being promoted out of the K-9 unit
at the Inglewood Police Department.
   ``He's getting retired simply because I'm getting old,'' Bell
quipped.
   Welz was stabbed, clubbed and kicked during his career but
remained fearless, his handler said. Like many loyal workers,
retirement was a bit of a let-down.
   ``For the first two weeks he lay by the front door and never
left it until I got home,'' Bell said. ``Now when I leave he just
whines. ... He's starting to adjust now.''
</TEXT>
