<FIRST>u a AM-CountyCentennial 1stLd-Writethru a0641 07-30 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-County Centennial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0641,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orange County, Calif.: From Utopia to Part of `Mega-Manhattan'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, `Kirkpatrick, who...' to CORRECT to Larimer
sted Laramie.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LYNN ELBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For much of its 100 years, California's
Orange County has represented a golden spot in a golden state:
cheap, plentiful land that sprouted first farms, then housing
tracts. It was a suburban sidekick to Los Angeles and a playland
that Mickey Mouse called home.
   But as the county of more than 2.2 million residents prepares to
mark its centennial Tuesday, experts say it has already rocketed
into the future as a metropolitan center where jobs _ not its
now-costly land _ are the lure, and where urban woes are
inescapable.
   ``Orange County has made the transition from being a suburb to
being a center of commerce,'' said Mark Baldassare, professor of
sociology at the University of California, Irvine. ``In the next
100 years, I expect it will become more like a dense urban region.''
   Jammed freeways and polluted air are the baggage carried by
growth, and won't be easily banished, he said. High-priced housing
also will remain part of the landscape.
   ``People will be coming here because it's a land of economic
opportunity, not some kind of utopia,'' Baldassare said.
   Only recently have people realized that the dream of an
uncrowded region, with homes affordable to all, has slipped away.
   It's within the last three years that surveys have found traffic
consistently named the county's No. 1 problem, said Tom Fortune,
spokesman for the Orange County Transportation Commission.
   Home prices in Orange County have soared beyond the rest of
costly California: The median home price in June was $251,674,
compared with $200,445 statewide, according to the California Board
of Realtors. That compares to a median price of $93,200 nationwide.
   ``It's as if the entire coast of Southern California is becoming
one mega-Manhattan, where only the wealthy can afford to live,''
said Baldassare.
   But the high cost of living has not stopped corporations,
foreign and domestic, from locating in Orange County, say
Baldassare and Bob Dunham, president of Newport Economics Group, a
Newport Beach, Calif.-based market research firm.
   Orange County, known to many Americans as the home of
Disneyland, already is a major player in the Pacific Rim economy,
attracting big Japanese manufacturers such as Toshiba and
Panasonic, said Dunham.
   Baldassare agreed that foreign investment will grow, and said
the county will continue to attract the aerospace and other
high-tech corporations like those that have set up shop in such new
developments as the Irvine Spectrum.
   In Irvine and other cities such as Costa Mesa, glossy high-rises
stand in strange proximity to reminders of Orange County's agrarian
past: patches of farmland that, for now, have escaped the bulldozer.
   Wes Kirkpatrick, 64, is one of the last cowboys still herding
cattle on dwindling Orange County ranchland.
   Kirkpatrick, who came to California from Larimer County, Colo.,
nearly 20 years ago, knows that the sliver of the old West, in the
canyon above the popular resort of Laguna Beach, will inevitably
vanish.
   ``It's a shame to see it go, especially for someone like me
raised on open country,'' Kirkpatrick said. ``But to a lot of
people it won't mean a thing.''
   Like the grazing land, the 61,000 acres of fragrant orange
trees, strawberry fields and orchards scattered throughout the
county seem like souvenirs of a past era. In the 1930s, 86 percent
of the county's 500,000-plus acres was given over to farming and
ranching.
   It was agriculture that brought the county's first boom. Efforts
at promoting farmland in the area surged in 1869, when the
completion of the transcontinental railroad opened the West for
expansion.
   By 1889, voters decided to sever the region from Los Angeles
County and form the County of Orange. The census the next year
counted 13,589 residents.
   It was the post-World War II search for affordable housing that
produced the most massive wave of immigrants.
   Orange County's 1950 population was 220,000. By 1960, it had
swelled to 704,000 residents, an increase of 220 percent in a
county that is roughly three-quarters the size of Rhode Island.
   The county's newcomers have maintained the primarily white,
middle-class profile that forecasters expect to persist, along with
a reputation for political conservatism.
   Once a bedroom community to Los Angeles, Orange County now finds
itself an urban center calling on less-developed inland counties
such as Riverside and San Bernardino to provide housing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
