<FIRST>r w AM-CongressRdp     07-30 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Sorting Through Budget Bills As Recess Nears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Congress characteristically lagging behind
schedule enters its last week before summer recess ready to race
through bills mapping how the government will spend nearly half its
$1.17 trillion budget next year.
   The House has lofty plans, hoping to complete the last seven of
the 13 annual appropriations bills for fiscal 1990 by Friday.
   The Senate, which by law can act on spending measures only after
receiving them from the House, might consider two appropriations
bills late in the week. It is likely to spend much of the rest of
its time trying to complete work on the $295 billion defense
authorization bill for next year.
   By law, Congress was supposed to have completed action on all
tax and deficit-reduction legislation by June 15, and the House was
to finish all 13 appropriations measures by June 30. The new fiscal
year begins Oct. 1.
   As usual, those dates have come and gone without the work being
done. The law provides no consequences for missing the deadlines,
and lawmakers will begin their four-week holiday on Aug. 5 with a
large pile of budget work awaiting their return.
   The House Ways and Means and the Senate Finance committees have
yet to decide how to raise $5.3 billion in new tax receipts for
next year called for in the congressional budget.
   Democrats are continuing to resist a capital gains tax cut that
President Bush is pressing, and Ways and Means Chairman Dan
Rostenkowski, D-Ill., has been talking with administration
officials in a search of a compromise.
   ``I don't know how long the discussion is going to continue,''
House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., said Friday.
   Spending work also is going slowly. The two chambers both have
approved only three of the 13 appropriations bills, and have yet to
work out compromise versions of any of them that can be sent to
Bush for his signature.
   The House will consider measures providing $1.6 billion for the
legislative branch and $8.7 billion for military construction on
Monday, and $5.8 billion for the Commerce, Justice and State
departments on Tuesday.
   On Wednesday it debates legislation providing $500 million for
the District of Columbia and $155 billion for the departments of
Labor, Health and Human Services and Education.
   An $11.9 billion transportation bill will be considered
Thursday, and the biggest of the spending bills _ a measure
providing $305 billion for defense spending _ will be considered
Friday.
   The Senate could consider a measure for the Treasury and Postal
Service expected to be about $18 billion, and a bill providing
about $1.6 billion for Congress' own operations.
   Both chambers also plan to pass a bill that will permit the
government to continue borrowing money so it can finance its
operations. The legal debt limit of $2.8 trillion should be
surpassed sometime in August, and congressional leaders hope to
pass legislation that would provide enough money to permit
borrowing through October.
   Such must-pass legislation often bogs down, however, because it
attracts unrelated, controversial amendments. Leaders are trying to
secure agreements to avoid that.
   The Senate on Monday resumes work on the defense authorization
bill, a measure that creates the programs that are then paid for by
appropriations.
   The House completed its version of the bill on Thursday, cutting
B-2 Stealth bomber spending, slashing the Star Wars program and
taking other liberties with Bush's defense priorities. Senate
leaders are trying to fashion a measure more closely resembling
White House preferences.
   Bush's nomination of William Lucas as the nation's chief civil
rights enforcer comes up in the Senate Judiciary Committee on
Tuesday.
   Many civil rights groups oppose Lucas, saying he lacks
experience. Republicans say the 61-year-old former Wayne County,
Mich., sheriff, who is black, has learned his lessons the hard way
in his climb from dishwasher to elected official.
   In the spotlight is undeclared Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., whose
vote could put Lucas over the top. Even if the Judiciary Committee
withholds its recommendation, however, the nomination is likely to
end up under debate on the Senate floor through an alternate route.
   Votes on a compromise savings and loan bailout bill also are
planned next week. The measure, worked out by negotiators from the
House and Senate last week, would cost $166 billion.
   Fireworks could still be touched off because the package ignores
Bush's proposal to remove $50 billion of the spending from the
budget, which would make the deficit appear smaller. Senate
Republicans could still block the plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
