<DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bruce Springsteen's attorneys have been
ordered to turn over all income tax records of the rock star's
employees to attorneys for two former workers who are suing him.
   Judge Florence Peskoe of Superior Court in Monmouth County told
the attorneys to comply with an earlier court order in a lawsuit in
which two former ``roadies'' for Springsteen claim they were
underpaid.
   Michael Batlan of Ocean Township and Douglas Sutphin of Long
Branch also claim they are owed thousands of dollars in overtime
from the ``Born in the U.S.A.'' tour in 1984 and 1985.
   Batlan quit in 1985 and Sutphin was fired that year. Both claim
they were full-time employees on call year round and should have
been paid at a rate slightly less than band members. Each made
about $50,000 a year working for Springsteen.
   Ms. Peskoe's order Friday was in response to a motion filed by
Stephen Schueler, attorney for the two men, to make Springsteen and
his organization, Thrill Hill Productions, comply with the previous
order and turn over financial records, including tax returns from
1973 to 1985.
   Ms. Peskoe gave Springsteen's attorneys 30 days to turn over the
records.
