<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-89 1450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     07-30 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Executes Two, Sentences 12 Others</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men were executed and a dozen other people
were sentenced to prison terms in the central city of Wuhan for
violence during recent pro-democracy demonstrations, it was
reported Sunday.
   Yu Chunting and Guo Zhenghua were sentenced to death and
executed by shots to the back of their heads Saturday afternoon for
stealing firearms and ammunition and killing a pregnant woman and a
girl while committing a robbery, the official Xinhua News Agency
said.
   One other person was given a suspended death sentence, two were
sentenced to life in prison, and nine received varying sentences
for beating police and soldiers, attacking government buildings,
stealing guns and ammunition, damaging railway facilities and
public vehicles and killing people.
   The report did not give the names of the other people convicted
or say who had committed which crimes or exactly when they occurred.
   Wuhan and about a dozen other provincial cities were rocked by
violent protests during the seven-week pro-democracy movement that
began in April. Television reports from Wuhan showed people burning
buses.
   Several dozen executions are known to have taken place since the
student-led protests were crushed in Beijing June 3-4. The
authorities previously directly linked only 12 people to the
protests. Many Chinese believe the number is far higher.
   The official media have reported more than 2,060 arrests
nationwide in connection with the protests, according to Associated
Press count. In recent weeks, however, the government has stopped
publicizing arrests and executions, apparently in part ot avoid
international criticism.
   Thousands of arrests are believed to be taking place secretly
nationwide.
   In Hong Kong on Sunday, a factory worker from the northern
Chinese Shanxi province denounced the Beijing government at a rally
and told the audience he lied at the official ideological education
sessions he had to attend.
   ``I made up something at the study group. But privately we said
all the official speeches were rubbish. It's so hypocritical,''
said the worker who identified himself as Li.
   He made the remarks during a rally attended by about 500 people
at a downtown park to condemn Chinese authorities for the
suppression of pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Li, who arrived in early July, is scheduled to return to China
in September when his visitor's permit expires. He came alone,
leaving his wife and two children in Taiyuan, provincial capital of
Shanxi about 250 miles southwest of Beijing.
   He said he would not mind staying in Hong Kong but would not be
bothered if he had to go back. He requested a television crew not
film his face.
   Hong Kong, a British colony at the southern tip of China, will
be reverted to Chinese rule in 1997. China promised under a 1984
Sino-British Agreement to maintain Hong Kong's capitalist system
for 50 years after 1997.
</TEXT>
