<FIRST>r i AM-Iran     07-30 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Wins 94.5 Percent of Vote in Iran's Presidential Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>By ALEX EFTY</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper on Sunday cautioned Iranians not
to expect miracles from the new government of Hashemi Rafsanjani,
who was elected president in a landslide.
   Final results show that Rafsanjani, who has been the Parliament
speaker, captured 94.5 percent of the presidential vote Friday.
   Just hours after the final results were announced, the official
Iranian media reported that Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze would arrive Monday on an official visit.
   Iran's relations with the West are strained, and Rafsanjani has
been looking to the Soviet Union to help rebuild industries that
were battered in Iran's eight-year war with Iraq.
   Constitutional amendments also approved Friday make the
presidency the most powerful post in the government. It should give
Rafsanjani more control over the government than any previous
president in the 10-year history of the Islamic republic.
   The radical Jomhuri Islami newspaper cautioned Sunday that
people shouldn't expect miracles to end soaring inflation, high
prices and widespread inflation.
   ``It would be wrong if some people were hoping that every
problem would be solved quickly once the new government takes
charge,'' the newspaper said in an editorial.
   Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi told a news conference
Sunday that the revamped constitution, which scraps the post of
prime minister, was approved by 97 percent of those casting ballots.
   The amendments are designed to eliminate rival power blocs that
have paralyzed decision-making for years and delayed economic and
social reforms.
   Despite reports of a low turnout, Mohtashemi said a record 70
percent of the country's eligible 24 million voters took part.
   He said Iranian security forces had blocked attempts to smuggle
in weapons and ammunition and arrested ``elements cooperating with
foreign agents'' but gave no further details.
   It was not immediately clear when Rafsanjani, a middle-ranking
cleric who emerged as Iran's most powerful politician after the
death of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on June 3, would take over.
   President Ali Khamenei, who succeeded Khomeini as Iran's supreme
leader, is due to step down as president when his second four-year
term ends in October.
   But he is expected to hand over power earlier so that Rafsanjani
can start tackling the country's economic problems.
   Rafsanjani hopes to revitalize the sluggish Iranian economy by
encouraging private investment and adopting a more laissez-faire
approach.
   He is also expected to gradually rebuild relations with Western
countries, which were severely strained by Khomeini's decree that
British author Salman Rushdie should be killed for allegedly
blaspheming Islam in his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Mohtashemi said the Rushdie affair ``is not an impediment on our
side'' to better relations with the West, but said the religious
decree still stands.
   ``If the Western world wants to have relations with the Islamic
world, it must deliver him to the Islamic world so the decree can
be executed. Otherwise this will remain a wound in the relations
between the two worlds,'' he said.
</TEXT>
