<HEAD>Democrat Raps President on Civil Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``Jackson said,'' to CORRECT to nomination
sted appointment.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson on Sunday claimed
President Bush has offered no substance to back up his professed
commitment to civil rights.
   Jackson, interviewed on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press,'' faulted
Bush for supporting recent Supreme Court rulings opposed by civil
rights leaders, for failing to strengthen the Civil Rights
Commission and for lacking a comprehensive plan to fight drugs.
   ``Reagan laid the tracks to set us back,'' Jackson said. ``So
far, Bush has put grease on those tracks and not any brakes.''
   He credited Bush for directing less antagonism toward civil
rights, but added: ``So far, no substance.''
   ``It's too early to grade him, but there are some bad papers,''
Jackson said. ``So far we are disappointed.''
   Jackson said Bush's nomination of a black lawyer, Republican
William Lucas, to serve as the Justice Department's chief civil
rights advocate was ``a sinister play on race.''
   Jackson said Lucas was unqualified for the position because he
lacks trial experience, but that there are other Republican
minorities who are suited to the job.
   ``We need a credible civil rights lawyer who we feel will argue
our case behind closed doors,'' Jackson said. ``How can you expect
someone to perform the ultimate surgery who has never faced a
patient? Mr. Lucas ... would be expected to preside over 200 civil
rights lawyers and he has never tried a case.''
   Jackson, who is moving his legal residence to Washington, again
sidestepped questions about whether he would run for mayor of the
District of Columbia in 1990.
   ``I have no plans to run for the mayor of D.C.,'' Jackson said.
``There is no race in D.C. this year, but I am a little closer to
the White House.''
   Asked about his aspirations for the presidency in 1992, Jackson
said, ``It's too early to make that decision, but based upon last
year's efforts I am encouraged.''
</TEXT>
