<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     07-30 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Turkish Sympathizer to Iran Planted Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported Sunday that a Turk
sympathetic to Iranian radicals posed as an airport worker in
Frankfurt and planted the bomb that destroyed Pan Am Flight 103.
   The weekly Observer, a respected newspaper, said that on orders
from an Iranian diplomat, the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command contacted Turks to plan the bombing that
killed 270 people on Dec. 21.
   The radical PFLP-GC has been a prime suspect in the bombing of
the Boeing 747 over Lockerbie, Scotland, while en route to New
York. It has denied involvement.
   The newspaper quoted unidentified Middle Eastern and official
Western intelligence sources.
   Police in Lockerbie, coordinating an international investigation
into the bombing, said they were unable to comment on the report.
   It quoted a U.S. official with ``close knowledge of the
inquiries into the bombing'' as saying, ``A very interesting and
potentially productive side of our investigation involves members
of the German Turkish groups. Our inquiries are beginning to point
to the involvement of Turkish fundamentalists.''
   It said, however, that German officials who questioned airport
workers after the bombing have ``refused to either support or
dismiss'' the Observer's account.
   The newspaper said five Turks involved in the plot worked or
posed as airport workers, two in maintenance, one in catering and
two in unspecified areas.
   One described as a young engineer planted the bomb in a suitcase
inside a cargo container, said the Observer. He left Germany for
Beirut shortly after the bombing, it said, without identifying the
man.
   In two articles, the newspaper said the plot grew out of
meetings between the PFLP-GC, Iranian diplomats and Revolutionary
Guards and a ``bewildering array of Arab extremists.''
   In a series of meetings in Beirut and Iran beginning July 12,
1988, the extremists conceived plans for a terrorist attack, the
paper said.
   It noted that nine days earlier, the United States missile
cruiser USS Vincennes had mistakenly shot down an Iranian passenger
jet, killing all 290 aboard.
   The newspaper said PFLP-GC leader Ahmed Jibril spoke at a Dec.
18 meeting of three aims: liberating Palestine by eliminating
Palestine Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat and other
``American collaborators,'' continuing the fight against America
and remaining in the background of any attack.
   The Turkish nationals were brought into the plot in September,
the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
