<HEAD>Several Injured in Bomb Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded Sunday outside a house
occupied by black South African exiles and injured several people,
witnesses said.
   The blast in Kamanga, a suburb of the capital, damaged nearby
houses but no one was believed killed, a neighbor said.
   The explosion left a 6-foot-deep crater in the sidewalk and
damaged part of a wall and a boundary fence, said the woman,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Police sealed off approaches to the scene, but it was not
immediately known if South Africans were among the unspecified
number of people injured.
   Police released no details of the bombing.
   Last month, the guerrilla-backed African National Congress
accused the white-dominated government in South Africa of mounting
a new sabotage campaign against its members and facilities in
Zambia.
   Three Lusaka-based ANC officials were injured in a series of
blasts at ANC offices in June.
   One person died near the ANC headquarters building in downtown
Lusaka when explosives he was carrying blew up, police said June 22.
   The ANC is the main guerrilla organization fighting white rule
in South Africa.
   In recent years, ANC facilities in black-governed southern
African nations have been regular targets of military and sabotage
attacks by South African agents.
