<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Railroad     07-30 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Railroad,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pravda Says Railroad Workers May Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Railroad workers have called a strike on the
Moscow-Leningrad line that could paralyze the northwestern Soviet
Union, the Communist Party daily Pravda said Sunday.
   The report of railroad workers' discontent over wages and work
conditions came after hundreds of thousands of coal miners in the
Ukraine and Siberia walked off their jobs earlier this month over
poor living and working conditions.
   Railroad director A. Zaitsev spoke of the strike calls in a
briefing for Soviet journalists, Pravda said. The report did not
say when the strike might occur.
   Pravda said a railroad strike would be an ``extraordinarily
dangerous action, leading to a very real catastrophe for the
northwest economic region.''
   Another walkout following the coal miners' strike would add to
the economic chaos and could make strikes more attractive to other
disgruntled Soviet workers.
   The Pravda article said transportation strikes were prohibited
in many countries, intimating that officials would not tolerate a
walkout.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev sided with the striking coal
miners against bureaucrats who he said were holding back reforms,
and he promised broad improvements in their lives. Most returned to
work.
   In a speech July 19 on the coal miners' strike, Gorbachev said
there had been calls for a railroad engineers' strike beginning
Aug. 1 and warned against it. Such a strike would damage efforts to
reform the economy and improve conditions for everyone, Gorbachev
said.
   Pravda, quoting the Moscow-Leningrad railroad's newspaper, said
a strike would shut down factories in the northeast Soviet Union
and cause ``chaos in our everyday lives.''
   It said railroad workers complained they were not given adequate
time to eat during their shifts. It said they claimed unjust wage
discrepancies among workers at stations along the 375-mile route.
   Pravda questioned why ``independent activists'' were making
demands rather than the unions that represent the railroad workers.
   Soviet unions long have done little but follow official policy,
and workers have begun voicing their demands outside the official
union structure.
</TEXT>
