<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-89 1616EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Governors     07-30 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bradley Tells Governors Not to Bank on Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley told the nation's
governors Sunday that dramatic changes in the Soviet Union could
mean future economic benefits for the United States but little
immediate opportunity for individual states.
   Bradley, D-N.J., who recently traveled throughout the Soviet
Union, said the United States should be ``rational capitalists, not
romantic capitalists'' in dealing with the Soviets.
   He cautioned against extending credit to the Soviets because,
``I don't want to help the Soviets avoid the choice between guns
and butter.''
   Efforts by Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev to improve the
economy will require reduced defense spending and therefore offer
the potential of arms agreements, Bradley said. But, he said, the
Soviet Union will have little money to spend on non-military deals
with the United States.
   ``It seems to me there's going to be very little way to make
very much money in the Soviet Union for a long time to come,'' he
said.
   The governors, meeting at the four-day, bipartisan National
Governors' Association, have been focusing on ways to improve U.S.
economic competitiveness and how states can enhance business
arrangements with other countries. President Bush plans to address
the group on Monday.
   Maine Gov. John McKernan, a Republican, asked Bradley how much
potential the Soviet changes could offer state businesses.
   ``Don't expect your Maine businessmen to be making billions in
the Soviet Union, unless they're willing to treat it as the
ultimate wildcat,'' Bradley said.
   Also at the conference was Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, who told the governors that the world economy's
increasing reliance on technology will mean states will have to
devote more attention to education.
   ``The major capital of the next century is going to be minds
that produce ideas,'' Greenspan told a gathering of association's
executive committee.
   ``More and higher quality education must be presumed to be
crucial in America's competition with our industrial partners for
economic world leadership,'' Greenspan said.
   Outside the meeting, about 50 abortion-rights demonstrators held
a brief rally to urge governors not to back efforts to restrict
access to abortions.
   The meeting is the governors' first since the Supreme Court gave
states greater leeway in regulating abortion. Governors steered
clear of the issue in their formal meetings, but abortion _ and the
political impact of the decision _ was being discussed in the halls.
   Delaware Gov. Michael Castle, a Republican, said abortion ``will
be a dominant issue'' in the states.
</TEXT>
