<FIRST>r p AM-Pepper'sSeat     07-30 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper's Seat,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats In Tight Race; Republican Hopes to Avoid Run-Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The niece of the late U.S. Rep. Claude Pepper, a
former city commissioner and a lawyer who has been linked to an
international arms dealer lead the Democratic field in Tuesday's
primary contest for Pepper's seat.
   On the Republican side, state Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen hopes to
win the nomination outright, then watch more Democratic
bloodletting in an Aug. 15 runoff vote.
   Her main obsctale to winning the 50 percent-plus-one margin
needed to clinch the 18th District nomination is the candidacy of
Carlos Perez, a wealthy conservative activist.
   Race has been an election issue in a city where the rapid growth
of the Hispanic population complicates existing tension between
whites and blacks. Some Hispanics see in the vote a chance to put
the first Cuban-American in Congress.
   Both GOP front-runners are Cuban-born, as is the Democrat
favored in recent polls, Rosario Kennedy.
   The special election to fill the Pepper's seat is to be held
Aug. 29. Pepper, who died May 30 at age 88, filled the seat since
1962.
   Some expect the voting to follow the recent pattern in Florida
politics: Democrats divide in their primary, then get conquered by
a well-funded Republican leading a united party.
   Republicans hold an unprecedented 10-8 lead in the state's
congressional delegation, won a U.S. Senate seat last year and will
try to re-elect Gov. Bob Martinez in 1990.
   ``It was bound to be a fierce campaign in the end, and the
beneficiary would be Ileana Ros-Lehtinen,'' said Phil Hamersmith, a
strategist for Ms. Kennedy. Hamersmith said he was confident the
Democrats would unite after the expected runoff.
   Ms. Kennedy, who resigned her Miami city commission seat to run,
is the unquestioned front-runner among the Democrats. She has the
endorsements of the AFL-CIO, The Miami Herald and state party
Chairman Simon Ferro.
   But she is given little chance of winning a majority against six
other candidates. Some strategists say that because turnout is
expected to be low among the district's 100,000 registered
Democrats, a candidate could reach the runoff with as few as 5,000
votes.
   Personalities and backgrounds have dominated the Democratic race.
   On Saturday, three of the Democratic contenders called on Ms.
Kennedy to withdraw from the race because of negative campaign
mailers sent out by her camp.
   Two of her opponents, lawyer Gerald Richman and businessman
Bernard Anscher, said they would be unable to support Ms. Kennedy
if she were the nominee. The other, Jo Ann Pepper, said she would
have to think hard about it.
   Ms. Kennedy's campaign aides said the mailers were necessary to
counter challenges to her ethics and attacks on her personal life
and Hispanic roots.
   Her campaign mailings highlighted Richman's defense of arms
dealer Sarkis Soghanalian. Richman, who used Soghanalian's plane to
fly to Tallahassee to meet the campaign qualifying deadline,
defended the arms dealer as a patriot.
   Polls show Ms. Pepper and Richman running closest to Ms.
Kennedy. But Anscher, black intellectual Marvin Dunn, black real
estate agent Sonny Wright and striking Eastern Airlines pilot John
Paul Rosser all hope to put together enough votes to slip into the
runoff.
   Richman, who is white, opens his speeches by calling the 18th
District ``an American seat.''
   Among registered Democratic voters in the district, 52 percent
are white, 32 percent are black and 16 percent are Hispanic.
   Ms. Pepper, the niece of the late congressman and one of his
closest companions the last few years, says she wants to continue
the Pepper agenda. A federal probation officer without experience
in elective office, she says she learned government in her travels
with Pepper.
   ``I am a Pepper,'' she said recently. ``I had the best teacher.
I think my opponents wish the could be a Pepper, too.''
   On the Republican side, Ms. Ros-Lehtinen raised a campaign-high
$200,000. She emphasizes her conservative views and legislative
experience. Her husband, U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen, called a
news conference last week to denounce Democratic charges that his
appearance in his wife's campaign advertising is unlawful.
   Perez, a fervent supporter of Ronald Reagan and Oliver North,
who has endorsed his candidacy, insists he can win, while former
North Miami Mayor John Stembridge and insurance broker David
Fleischer are GOP longshots.
</TEXT>
