<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Sisulu     07-30 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Sisulu,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Leader Returns Home to Tumultuous Welcome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-apartheid leader
Albertina Sisulu returned Sunday from a trip abroad and more than
200 singing, dancing supporters welcomed the 71-year-old black
woman home.
   Mrs. Sisulu had been granted a 31-day passport to allow her to
accept an invitation from President Bush to meet with him in
Washington.
   She met with Bush last month and led a delegation of leaders of
the banned United Democratic Front in meetings with British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher, Swedish Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson
and with officials in Belgium and France.
   ``I am so happy to be back with my people,'' Mrs. Sisulu told
the airport crowd.
   It took her an hour to get her luggage. The South African Press
Association quoted a police spokesman at the airport as saying only
that it had been ``held up.''
   The independent news agency also quoted a political activist,
who asked not to be identified by name, as saying police ``reminded
Mrs. Sisulu about her conditions of house arrest and warned her not
to make a statement at the airport.''
   Mrs. Sisulu had urged Bush and Mrs. Thatcher to impose more
sweeping economic sanctions against South Africa to force the
white-controlled government to negotiate with the black majority.
Neither has endorsed such an idea.
   The welcoming crowd at the airport sang a Zulu anthem ``God
Bless Africa'' and many raised their fists in a black-power salute.
They danced and pressed around Mrs. Sisulu as she walked to her car.
   Some held placards. One read, ``You strike a woman, you strike a
rock!'' _ the slogan of a 1956 black women's protest of a law
requiring blacks to carry passes. Mrs. Sisulu was one of the
leaders of that protest campaign.
</TEXT>
