<FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-89 1729EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Women'sCaucus     07-30 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Women's Caucus,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Women's Political Caucus Convention To Focus On Abortion
Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Cybill Shepherd and U.S. Rep.
Patricia Schroeder, D-Colo., are among those expected to speak on
abortion at the National Women's Political Caucus convention here
this week.
   At the four-day convention opening Thursday, leaders plan to
unveil a national plan to tap the voting strength of people who
favor abortion rights in the wake of the U.S. Supreme Court ruling
giving states more latitude in governing abortion.
   Caucus Chairwoman Irene Natividad said the organization will be
targeting legislative seats in several states to diminish
anti-abortion strength.
   ``I see choice, the right to reproductive freedom, as the
politicizing issue for the women of the `90s, the same way the ERA
was the politicizing issue for the women of my generation, the `60s
and `70s,'' said Natividad.
   ``In many ways, it is perhaps a clearer issue for a lot of
women, because it hits a lot of women more directly. ERA was more
of a class issue or group issue. Choice is an individual issue,''
she said.
   The high court's July 3 abortion ruling is bringing a new sense
of urgency to the biennial convention of the 77,000-member caucus,
whose goal for two decades has been to put more women in public
office, organizers say.
   It changes the focus of the convention which is expected to draw
1,500 delegates, alternates and guests, said Dede Wolfson,
chairwoman of the Minnesota Women's Political Caucus and convention
host.
   ``The focus would not be predominantly on the abortion issue if
the Webster case hadn't occurred. The focus would have been on how
to get women elected. We'll still focus on how to get women
elected, but there will be two major components at this
convention,'' she said.
   In Webster vs. Reproductive Health Services, Inc., the Supreme
Court upheld certain restrictive provisions of a Missouri law on
abortion.
   Natividad, Wolfson and Minnesota officials who are caucus
members look at the Supreme Court's ruling as an erosion of women's
rights, but not necessarily without political value.
   ``It's going to energize the women's movement,'' said
Minneapolis City Council Member Barbara Carlson.
   ``Women have become so busy with their own lives and careers
that what they needed was something like this to coalesce women.
... For the first time, I almost feel like the suffragettes must
have felt. They took to the streets. I suspect women are going to
do that again,'' Carlson said.
   Natividad said abortion rights will not move to the top of the
caucus agenda if abortion restrictions tighten.
   The caucus is the political arm of the women's movement and
should remain committed to getting women elected to office, though
it will continue to be concerned with other women's issues, she
said.
</TEXT>
