<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-China     07-30 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-China,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Breaks out of Diplomatic Isolation At Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cambodia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conference of 19 countries seeking peace in
Cambodia has allowed China to break the diplomatic isolation
imposed after the June crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in
Beijing.
   Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen met Sunday with French
Foreign Minister Roland Dumas and British Foreign Secretary John
Major.
   He was expected to meet U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker
III, Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark and others before leaving
Paris.
   Baker and Qian were seated next to each other at the conference
table, where the foreign ministers were arranged in alphabetical
order by the spellings of their country's names in French.
   U.S. officials said on condition of anonymity that the two
exchanged ``cordial greetings,'' but did not discuss substantive
issues.
   President Bush ruled out high-level U.S. visits to China after
the military suppression of the pro-democracy movement. But Baker
does not consider the ban a barrier to meeting with the Chinese
foreign minister outside Beijing, the officials said.
   French officials said Dumas' meeting with Qian kept strictly to
the Cambodia issue. When Qian noted with regret the cooling of
bilateral relations, Dumas called attention to the reason for the
chill, they said.
   Canadian Foreign Minister Joe Clark told reporters that he would
restate his country's objections to the crackdown when he met with
Qian, but said, ``We won't have a solution to Cambodia without the
active participation of China.''
   China supports the Khmer Rouge, the strongest guerrilla faction
facing the Vietnamese-backed government of Premier Hun Sun. Most
other countries contend that a chief aim of the peace process is
finding a way to keep the Khmer Rouge from returning to power.
   The Khmer Rouge killed hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
during its three-year reign of Cambodia, ended by a Vietnamese
invasion in 1978. Vietnam is to withdraw its estimated 60,000
troops from Cambodia by late September.
</TEXT>
