<FIRST>r i AM-India-SriLanka     07-30 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Sri Lanka,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian and Sri Lankan Officials Meet on Indian Troop Withdrawal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sri Lanka's foreign minister met with
Indian officials Sunday to negotiate a date for the withdrawal of
45,000 Indian peacekeeping troopers from Sri Lanka.
   No details were given. Negotiations were to resume Monday.
   Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne arrived Saturday,
the day after India withdrew 600 soldiers in a gesture that ended a
two-month diplomatic stalemate and led to the weekend talks.
   The Indian forces came to this island off India's southern coast
under a peace agreement signed two years ago to help disarm Tamil
rebels demanding autonomy in northern Sri Lanka.
   But the fighting continued and Sri Lankan President Ranasinghe
Premadasa demanded the Indian troopers leave by July 29, the second
anniversary of the Indian-brokered peace accord.
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi refused, saying the agreement
had not been fully implemented.
   In Sri Lanka, people rushed to shops to stock up on supplies
Sunday as the government relaxed a nationwide curfew for 10 hours.
The curfew had been imposed at midnight Thursday to thwart violence
on the anniversary of the peace agreement.
   The curfew went back into effect at 4 p.m. Sunday, but state-run
radio said it would be lifted at 5 a.m. Monday. It reported
military officials said the anniversary had passed peacefully.
   United News of India said Wijeratne met for 2{ hours with Indian
Defense Minister Krishna Chandra Pant and then held talks with
Foreign Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao. The news agency said the
discussions were ``conducted in a warm and friendly atmposhere''
but did not elaborate.
   It is believed Wijeratne also discussed a cease-fire between
Indian troops and the dominant Sri Lankan rebel group, the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
   The Tamil Tigers have started their own talks with Premadasa's
government over ending their 6-year-old separatist campaign in
which at least 11,000 people have been killed, including about
1,000 Indian soldiers.
   The Indian troops were supposed to disarm the Tamil Tigers and
other militant groups under the peace accord, which also promised
limited autonomy to the minority Tamils.
   But the Tamil Tigers pulled out of the agreement and attacked
the Indian soldiers.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's
population of 16 million. They claim discrimination by the Buddhist
Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population and control
the government and military.
</TEXT>
