<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-30 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain in Missouri and Much of South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain caused flooding Sunday in Missouri, where winds gusted to
40 mph in some areas, and scattered showers and thunderstorms were
reported throughout the South.
   Roads and fields throughout central Missouri were flooded with
rain brought on by a cluster of thunderstorms that moved in from
eastern Nebraska.
   Columbia, Mo., reported nearly 6 inches of rain, Edinia got
nearly 4 and Centralia measured just over 3 inches of rain. Brief,
heavy rain and gusty winds to 40 mph were reported at Cape
Girardeau.
   Showers and thunderstorms were rumbling along a stationary front
that stretched from the Missouri River Valley into the lower Ohio
River Valley.
   Thunderstorms with potentially heavy rain were across southern
Illinois and southern Indiana into eastern Kentucky.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms developed in warm and
humid air over central Alabama and eastern North Carolina. Showers
and thunderstorms were scattered across southern Florida.
   Rain and thunderstorms clustered over northeast Colorado Sunday
morning. Over 3 inches of rain fell in two hours near Fleming, Colo.
   Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered across parts of
central and southern New York. Gusty thunderstorm winds blew down
trees and power lines in Wilton and Saratoga Springs.
   The nation's low Sunday morning was 40 degrees at Houlton,
Maine, and Truckee, Calif.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Salinas, Calif., to 105 at Needles, Calif.
   Monday's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
in the lower half of the Mississippi Valley, the lower Ohio and
Tennessee valleys, the mid-Atlantic states and the Gulf Coast
region.
   Showers and thunderstorms were to be more numerous in western
Pennsylvania, eastern Kentucky, Mississippi and Louisiana, the
eastern slopes of the Colorado Rockies, northern Arizona, New
Mexico and western Montana.
   Rain was expected in the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures were to reach the 80s or 90s across much of
the nation, with 70s in the Pacific Northwest, the upper Great
Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley and New England; around 100 degrees
over parts of the western Dakotas and northern Montana, northwest
Texas and southwest Oklahoma; and between 100 and 115 degrees
across the desert Southwest.
