<FIRST>r a AM-DisabledVets     07-30 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disabled Vets,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Bush First Chief Executive to Address DAV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health care for veterans, diminishing clout in
Congress and a visit by President Bush comprise the agenda for the
68th convention of the Disabled American Veterans, which began
Sunday.
   Bush will be the first president to address the 1.1 million
member organization, said DAV spokesman Walter Phillips.
   Bush's appearance here Monday afternoon comes just months after
he signed into law a bill elevating the Veterans Administration to
cabinet level as the Department of Veterans Affairs.
   The convention comes amid concern veterans are losing some of
their clout on Capitol Hill. That notion must be reversed,
according to DAV national commander Billy E. Kirby of Clifton,
Texas.
   ``It is your future in jeopardy, your well-being that's
threatened unless you get involved,'' Kirby told delegates
attending the opening session Sunday.
   Kirby said one of his proudest moments as head of the DAV came
this past spring when he went to the White House to witness ``a
30-year-old dream become a reality'' with the elevation of the VA
to cabinet status.
   ``With a stroke of the president's pen, veterans stepped forward
to the Cabinet table and into the national policy-setting arena,''
Kirby said in remarks prepared for the convention's opening session.
   Still, Kirby said, there is concern that America's veterans lack
clout in Congress.
   Influential Congressmen have repeatedly warned ``that our
programs are in deep trouble if more veterans don't get involved,''
he said.
   ``We must find ways to harness the involvement and advocacy we
see disabled vets practicing in their hometowns,'' Kirby said. ``We
must channel more of that enthusiasm for service toward Washington,
and into the halls of Congress.''
   Veterans health care will be a major area of concern for the
6,000 people attending the convention, according to Phillips.
   Tommy Clack, who lost both legs and his right arm during a
firefight in Vietnam in 1969, was honored Sunday as the Disabled
American Veterans' man of the year.
   Clack has worked for the past decade at Atlanta's Veterans
Administration Medical Center, where he spent much of his 21-month
recovery following his injury in Vietnam.
   Clack, 42, of Stone Mountain, Ga., holds Silver Star, Bronze
Star and Purple Heart medals. He has spoken about veterans' issues
in all 50 states.
   ``God left me with my brain intact, my mouth in gear and my left
arm to be independent. What else do we need in life?'' he said in a
recent interview. ``We're lucky to be alive, and let's go forward.''
</TEXT>
