<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0696 07-30 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0696,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Says Aoun Has Frog Missiles; Shelling Kills Four</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs updating casualties and more fire details.
Pickup 5th graf: Police said Syrian...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanon's ambassador to Iraq was quoted
Sunday as confirming that Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun
has acquired missiles and other weapons from Iraq to bolster his
war effort against Syrian forces.
   Artillery duels raged between Syrian and Christian forces,
setting huge fires in residential districts in the city's Moslem
and Christian sectors.
   Four people were killed and 52 were wounded in the shelling that
began after sundown and continued for nine hours.
   The casualties raised the toll to 506 killed and 2,118 wounded
since the current round of fighting in Lebanon's 14-year-old civil
war broke out March 8, pitting Aoun's 20,000 troops against the
Syrians and their Druse Moslem allies.
   Fire brigades in east and west Beirut said they were unable to
battle the fires, which gutted several apartment buildings and
gasoline stations, because of water shortages.
   Police said Syrian gunners blasted Aoun's presidential palace in
suburban Baabda east of Beirut with rockets and that Aoun was in
the underground bunker of the two-story building.
   Several shells exploded around the office of Syrian-backed
acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss. Officials said Hoss was at his
home about a mile away from his office.
   Aoun heads a Christian military Cabinet vying for legitimacy
with Hoss' Syrian-backed Moslem government.
   Shells also hit near the buildings housing The Associated Press,
United Press International, Reuters and the Agence France-Presse
news agencies near west Beirut's Hamra commercial thoroughfare.
There were no casualties among journalists.
   ``Yes, Lebanon does possess Frog-7 missiles supplied by Iraq,''
Hikmat Awad, Lebanon's ambassador to Iraq, was quoted as saying in
the conservative Beirut newspaper Al-Anwar.
   ``Lebanon has much more sophisticated weapons which, if
revealed, will make everyone forget about the Frog-7s,'' Awad was
quoted as saying. He did not elaborate.
   Awad's confirmation was the first by a Lebanese Christian
official that Aoun's forces have Frog-7s, which can hit the Syrian
capital of Damascus about 40 miles away if fired from Lebanon's
central mountains in the Christian enclave.
   The report said Awad spoke when he arrived in Christian east
Beirut Saturday for talks with Aoun.
   Syria and Iraq are governed by bitterly competitive wings of the
Arab Socialist Baath Party.
   Aoun has vowed a ``war of liberation'' to drive out 40,000
Syrian troops stationed in Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping
mandate from the Arab League.
   It was not immediately clear why Awad would confirm the presence
of Frog-7 missiles when Aoun has not. The state-run Iraqi media has
previously said that Frog-7 missiles had been sent to Aoun's army.
   Awad did not say how many of the missiles Aoun has. The missile
has a range of about 43 miles and carries a warhead of 1,200 pounds
of high explosives.
   The Syrians have been demanding the removal of the Frog-7s from
the Christian side as a precondition for a cease-fire and lifting
of their land and sea blockade of the Christian enclave.
   Syrian gunboats have been searching ships, and Syrian artillery
has been shelling the coast to prevent supplies from landing at the
enclave.
   Intransigence on both sides has stymied peacemaking efforts by
an Arab League summit committee made up of King Fahd of Saudi
Arabia, King Hassan II of Morocco and Algerian President Chadli
Bendjedid.
   Their foreign ministers met in Rabat, Morocco, on Saturday to
discuss new ways to stop the fighting in Lebanon.
   Police estimate more than one million residents have fled Beirut
since March, turning what was once the most glamorous capital in
the Middle East into a virtual ghost city.
</TEXT>
