<FIRST>r a AM-BeachConditions     07-30 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beach Conditions,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Minor Problems, Beach Tourists Are Coming Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business has been slower than usual
this summer at many East Coast beaches, but bad weather apparently
is doing more to keep tourists away than the threat of pollution.
   For the past two summers, reports of washed-up medical waste,
floating garbage and high counts of fecal coliform bacteria scared
tens of thousands of tourists away.
   To restore public confidence _ and protect the tourist-dependent
economies of beach communities _ some states have undertaken
massive weekly ocean water testing programs. Better information
about the actual danger, or lack of danger, from pollution also has
helped, some say.
   ``People are not panicking as much because they're more
informed,'' said Noreen Bodman, director of the New Jersey Division
of Travel and Tourism. ``They also know we're doing all we can to
keep the beaches clean and safe.''
   Preliminary figures from Virginia Beach, Va., show tourism was
down 7 percent in June from last year, but officials there are
blaming the weather.
   In Rhode Island, a cool and rainy period in early July also
caused the number of tourists to drop, say tourism officials.
   In Rehoboth Beach, Del., tourism has fluctuated because of bad
weather, said city manager Gregory Ferrese.
   ``I think the day trippers have decreased dramatically because
of the weather conditions,'' Ferrese said.
   On the other hand, Jones Beach on New York's Long Island has
experienced one of the East Coast's most dramatic increases in
beachgoers. Between July 7 and July 26 last year, 635,000 people
used the beach, but that number rose to 1.1 million during the same
period this year.
   At Rehoboth, hotel and motel reservations for August are
promising, Ferrese said. In New Jersey, Ms. Bodman predicted strong
end-of-summer turnout.
   Environmental reports suggest that bacteria contamination has
closed back bays more often than ocean beaches, largely because
bays are often catch basins for storm runoff.
   However, ocean beaches have not been spared.
   Earlier this month, 13 beaches in Cape May County in southern
New Jersey _ including all beaches in the popular town of Wildwood
_ were plagued for several days by high bacteria counts after heavy
rains that caused storm sewers to overflow.
   But tourists did not stay away. Tourism experts point to
educational campaigns that have taught the public what is dangerous
waste and what is not.
   Storm water runoff, for instance, is a natural phenomenon that
usually dissipates quickly.
   Syringes have been found on beaches in several states this year,
but haven't prompted instant beach closures as in past years.
   One New York official blamed the media for scaring tourists away
from Long Island beaches by reporting on medical debris that washed
ashore.
   ``People were frightened about something they didn't know
anything about,'' said Joseph Lescinski, superintendent of Jones
Beach State Park.
   One episode demonstrated the importance of tourist revenue to
beach communities. A group of merchants dropped chlorine tablets in
the ocean off Cape May County in a futile attempt to kill bacteria.
   Other communities have mounted organized efforts.
   In Long Island, and New Jersey, helicopters are used for daily
patrols of the waters. New York Harbor gets special attention to
help target shore-bound garbage slicks so they can be swept up
before they reach the beaches.
   Since January, New York City has covered its garbage barges with
netting to hold down the 14,000 tons of debris barged daily to a
dump on Staten Island.
</TEXT>
