<FIRST>r a AM-RadioReunion     07-30 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Radio Reunion,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blind Couple Marry After Reunion Via Radio Broadcast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It had been 20 years since Jenny and Ted
attended a school for the blind in a small Massachusetts town, but
his voice on the radio was unmistakable and the two have been
reunited.
   Edwin Henry McCaw, 43, and Jeannette Gates, 40, were married
Saturday after they got in touch again through the radio show McCaw
has conducted since 1976.
   ``I knew from friends that he worked at a South Shore radio
station, but I didn't think I would be able to hear it from where I
lived,'' said Gates, who lives in Beverly.
   When in 1986 she heard a radio voice like McCaw's, she called
the station, but there was no answer. The following week, she
called the station with a request for: ``Please Don't Leave Me'' by
Fats Domino.
   ``Well, one thing led to another and I started sending out songs
to Jenny in Beverly,'' McCaw said. ``One night, the phone rang and
it was Jenny. She said, `Ted, we need to do some serious talking.'
''
   The couple married Saturday in the Open Door Church of God here
and rode off in the rumble seat of a 1934 Ford to a reception in
Hanson, their hometown.
   McCaw graduated from the Perkins School for the Blind in
Watertown in 1966 and went to work as a mechanic helping to restore
old buses. Every Sunday night he broadcasts a 1950s music program,
``Off the Wall,'' for WADT-FM in Marshfield.
   Mrs. McCaw, who was divorced after an eight-year marriage to a
partly-blind musician, has worked for the Morgan Memorial Goodwill
Industries and for the Chubb Insurance Group in Boston.
   ``I remember when I was in the sixth grade and Jen was in the
fourth,'' McCaw said. ``She'd cry and I'd pick her up and carry her
on my shoulder all over the school.
   ``I was late for class a lot,'' he said.
</TEXT>
