<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0628 07-30 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,0804</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Restricts Army Demolitions of Palestinian Homes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with two more Palestinian deaths, PLO
official meeting with Labor Party; Edits to Trim; No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Sunday restricted the
army's right to demolish homes of Palestinians suspected of
involvement in the uprising in the occupied lands.
   In its strongest move to limit army powers in the 19-month-old
rebellion, the court said the military must allow appeals before
destroying houses, a practice that has been denounced by the United
States and other Western nations and human rights groups.
   In the occupied West Bank, soldiers shot to death a 17-year-old
Palestinian, the army and Arab reporters said. In the occupied Gaza
Strip, an Israeli settler shot and killed a Palestinian
stone-thrower after Arabs barraged his car with stones, a police
spokesman said.
   Two other Arabs died of wounds suffered in earlier clashes with
soldiers, hospital officials said.
   Police also arrested eight Israelis on suspicion of fomenting
rebellion as members of the Free State of Judea movement, which
calls for founding a Jewish nation in the West Bank.
   The 18-page Supreme Court ruling was in response to an appeal by
the Association for Civil Rights in Israel.
   The three-member court ordered the army to inform owners of
houses slated for demolition that they could appeal to a military
commander and the Supreme Court.
   It said that in some cases, a house may be sealed before the
appeal hearing, ``as opposed to demolition, which is irreversible.''
   Presiding Judge Meir Shamgar also said the army has the right to
immediately demolish a house in case of ``operational military
needs,'' such as in combat.
   A military spokesman said 227 houses have been demolished in the
occupied territories during the uprising. Palestinian groups say
the number is higher.
   The U.S. State Department in February said the demolitions
violated the Geneva Conventions on human rights and ignored due
process because suspects' houses were torn down before they were
tried.
   The Israeli Foreign Ministry responded by saying the measure was
used ``only in very exceptional circumstances as dictated by
compelling security requirements.''
   In court arguments, the state prosecutor's office and the army
said an appeal period is granted automatically according to army
policy, except in ``serious and exceptional cases'' that involve
fatalities or injuries.
   Justice Minister Dan Meridor said in an army radio interview
that there was no reason to change the law. ``We are talking about
the use of emergency regulations,'' he said.
   The civil rights association applauded the decision of the
court, which in the past has rejected a number of individual
appeals involving house demolitions.
   ``Our association has always believed that the drastic step of
demolition of houses ... is a form of collective punishment which
is not justified,'' said David Presler, a member of the
association, on Israel radio.
   ``However, from the legal point of view, the maximum we could do
... was to guarantee the procedural rights of people whose houses
were about to be demolished.''
   Since the uprising began in December 1987, at least 525
Palestinians have been killed in clashes with army troops and
Israeli settlers in the occupied lands. Thirty-eight Israelis have
died.
   In addition, Palestinians have killed 85 fellow Arabs accused of
collaborating with Israel during the uprising.
   The army and Palestinian sources gave conflicting reports on the
death Sunday of Iyad Abdullah Abdel Qader, the 17-year-old killed
in the West Bank village of Ras Karka. The army said he was shot by
soldiers who opened fire on stone-throwing youths along a highway.
   Villagers told Arab reporters Abdel Qader was shot in the head
at close range by soldiers who sneaked into the village Saturday
and opened fire without warning.
   In the second incident, a settler opened fire with a pistol
after his car was stoned as it passed the Arab town of Beit Hanun,
Gaza police spokesman Yigal Golan said. A 25-year-old Arab resident
was rushed to a nearby hospital, where he died on arrival, Golan
said. He would not release the victim's name.
   Police identified the settler as David Shtibi from the Gaza
Strip Jewish settlement of Rafah Yam.
   At least 2,500 Jewish settlers live surrounded by almost 800,000
Palestinians in the Gaza Strip.
   Also Sunday, Farouk Ata, 25, a resident of the West Bank's
Tulkarem refugee camp, died of wounds suffered last week in a clash
with troops, hospital officials said.
   Ahmad Fattah Ghaleb, 18, died in a Ramallah hospital Sunday from
stomach wounds suffered in a clash with soldiers in the West Bank
village of Beit Lid, hospital officials said. The army confirmed
his death.
</TEXT>
