<FIRST>r a AM-ArsenicPoisonings 1stLd-Writethru a0646 07-30 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arsenic Poisonings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0646,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Ordinary Neighborhood Lady' Accused in Arsenic Poisonings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, `The probe ..., to CORRECT victim's name to
Parsons, sted Parson.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suspect in a growing list of
possible arsenic poisonings is a 56-year-old retired grocery clerk
who once sang in the church choir and is the new wife of a
minister, authorities say.
   ``We're talking about an average, ordinary, neighborhood lady,''
said Alamance County Sheriff Richard Frye. ``If she had walked into
my office a couple of weeks ago, I would not have known her.''
   Blanche Taylor Moore is being held without bond, charged with
using arsenic to kill her first husband, James Taylor, in 1973, and
her boyfriend, Raymond Reid, in 1986.
   She also is charged with assault with intent to kill in the
arsenic poisoning of her present husband, the Rev. Dwight Moore,
still in a Greensboro hospital. On Thursday, the investigation
expanded to nine possible poisoning victims, eight of whom died.
   ``She told me this whole scenario is like a nightmare stalking
her,'' her attorney, Mitchell McEntire, said after visiting Mrs.
Moore in jail. ``It keeps stalking her.''
   ``The investigation is ongoing and it will continue as long as
police receive information,'' said District Attorney Steve Balog.
   Authorities were checking out every lead, the prosecutor said,
including tips from the public.
   ``This investigation is headed a long way from here,'' said
Burlington police Lt. Detective Steve Lynch.
   On Friday, Dr. John Butts of the state medical examiner's office
said an autopsy on Mrs. Moore's father, Parker D. Kiser Sr., showed
he had ingested arsenic in the weeks before his 1966 death, but
that his death was actually caused by heart failure.
   Lynch said the investigation of Kiser's death remains open.
   ``No immediate charges are planned until the investigation is
complete and the district attorney has an opportunity to evaluate
the case,'' he said Friday.
   Mrs. Moore has not been charged in any of the new investigations.
   ``In no way are we implying that these people were murdered,''
Lynch said. ``But as a result of some phone calls, we began to have
some unanswered questions.''
   Mrs. Moore is scheduled to be arraigned Aug. 28 on the murder
and assault charges.
   ``She's a good Christian lady who has lived her whole life
quietly,'' said her attorney. ``Now people are pointing fingers at
her.''
   Police began investigating Mrs. Moore after Moore was admitted
to North Carolina Memorial Hospital in Chapel Hill in May shortly
after their honeymoon with an illness diagnosed as arsenic
poisoning.
   The probe raised questions about four deaths of people linked
with Mrs. Moore. They included her father, Taylor, Reid and a
former co-worker, Mabel Jessie Parsons.
   The bodies of Taylor, Reid and Kiser were exhumed for autopsies.
   On Wednesday, Lynch sent to Butts the medical records of Mrs.
Parsons, 61, and three more possible victims: Joseph M. Mitchell,
57, also a co-worker; Ina P. Vinson, a retired Southern Bell
employee, and John W. Reiber, 77.
   On Thursday, the list of possible victims grew to nine with the
addition of Mrs. Moore's mother-in-law, Isla Taylor.
   Mrs. Moore, who declined a request for an interview, maintains
through her attorney that she is innocent.
   The events of the last few weeks have sent a shock wave through
the mill village of Carolina, on the outskirts of Burlington, where
Mrs. Moore lived briefly with her new husband prior to his
hospitalization May 7.
   ``Nobody, nobody suspected anything,'' said Wayne Hackney, who
operates a small grocery store and gas pump near the 130-member
Carolina United Church of Christ, where Moore began preaching five
years ago.
   ``The man didn't have any money. He's just a preacher,'' said
Larry Johnson, one of Hackney's customers.
   Another customer who declined to give his name said: ``I'd hate
to be in her shoes if I did it or not.''
   McEntire said he asked Mrs. Moore whether she had anything to do
with the cases in which she is charged.
   ``She said if the evidence is that they died of arsenic
poisoning, they either ingested it accidentally or someone did it
in a fashion to make it appear she did it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
