<SECOND>AM-Violinist Arrest, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0703,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acclaimed Musician Can't Put Up Instrument for Bail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 3rd, `Fodor, 39... to UPDATE with quotes
from father and ex-wife; picks up 4th graf pvs, `A family...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TISBURY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acclaimed violinist Eugene Fodor Jr. was
jailed after a judge refused to accept his 300-year-old violin to
guarantee bail on charges he broke into a motel room on Martha's
Vineyard.
   Fodor, who has performed internationally and at the White House,
was held over the weekend on breaking-and-entering and cocaine
possession charges after being arrested Thursday in a motel room,
said Tisbury Police Sgt. Justin Welch. On Friday, an Edgartown
District judge set bail at $50,000 and refused to accept the violin.
   Fodor, 39, is a native of Denver who lives in New York City. He
gained fame in 1974 when he became the first American to share top
honors at the Tchaikovsky violin competition in Moscow, and he has
recorded for RCA.
   The violinist's father said he did not have any warning that his
son may be in trouble until he learned of the arrest.
   ``The first I knew about it was when I read today's paper,''
Eugene Fodor Sr. of Morrison, a Denver suburb, said Saturday. Fodor
planned to travel to Edgartown, Mass., to attend his son's court
appearance.
   Fodor's ex-wife, Susan Davis of Vienna, Va., said she was
stunned to learn about Fodor's arrest and his attempt to use the
violin as surety for bond.
   Davis, who was married to Fodor between 1978 and 1985, said
Fodor contacted her early Friday ``because he wanted me to know
what was going on.''
   ``He sounded very frightened and said he didn't have much time
to talk,'' Davis said.
   A family member in Manhattan, who spoke Sunday on condition of
anonymity, said the incident likely stems from Fodor's recent drug
problem, which may be rooted in the very ferocity that fires the
violinist's creativity and craft.
   ``The only explanation I can think of is that he does everything
in a thorough way,'' she said. ``He's a genius in his work and he
devotes all his energy to his work. He's very intense in whatever
he does.''
   Hotel maids making early morning rounds noticed someone in a
room that was listed as unoccupied, said a manager at the Vineyard
Harbor Motel who declined to give his name. When they asked where
he came from he slammed the door. Motel workers called police and
Fodor was arrested.
   Fodor was arraigned Friday on Martha's Vineyard on charges of
breaking and entering in the night with intent to commit a felony;
trafficking in cocaine, possession of cocaine with intent to
distribute; possession of a hypodermic needle; possession of
heroin; and possession of a dangerous weapon _ a dagger, police
said.
</TEXT>
