<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--Governors-Drugs     07-30 0137</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Governors-Drugs,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mid-Atlantic Governors Sign Anti-Drug Compact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governors of six Mid-Atlantic states signed
an agreement Sunday pledging regional cooperation and planning in
the battle against drugs.
   The governors of Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania,
Virginia and West Virginia signed a ``Middle Atlantic Governor's
Compact on Drug and Alcohol Abuse'' at a meeting during the
National Governors' Conference.
   The agreement says the states will share information and
strategic planning on drugs and alcohol, develop coordinated drug
education programs, and, ``where possible'' establish uniform drug
laws.
   ``We know that drug dealers don't care about state borders, and
neither should we when it comes to setting goals and strategy'' in
fighting drugs, said Gov. Robert Casey of Pennsylvania. ``If we try
to solve these problems alone, state by state, it's going to be
extremely difficult.''
