<HEAD>Mozambique's Ruling Party Adopts Non-Marxist Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates at the ruling party's
national congress adopted a platform Sunday that drops all
references to Marxism and calls for less state control of the
economy.
   It also says some educational, health and housing services
should be turned over to the private sector.
   The Front for the Liberation of Mozambique, or Frelimo, came to
power in 1975 when Mozambique gained independence from Portugal and
established one-party rule in a Marxist-Leninst state.
   President Joaquim Chissano said at the beginning of the
week-long congress that Frelimo remains committed to socialism but
should ``express the aspirations of the entire people.''
   The party's new platform removes all references to ``class
struggle'' and Western imperialism. Mozambique has improved
relations with Western countries, which provide substantial aid for
the nation and its 15 million people.
