<SECOND>AM-Cyprus,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greek Orthodox Bishop and Priest Released by Turkish Cypriots</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Bishop identified by one name in 2nd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Greek Orthodox bishop and a priest were
freed Sunday after being seized July 19 by Turkish-Cypriot police
during a protest in the United Nations buffer zone in the divided
city.
   Bishop Chrysostomos of Larnaca and the Rev. Giorgos Chrysostomou
were the last to be released of 108 Greek Cypriots arrested during
the demonstration marking the anniversary of the 1974 Turkish
invasion of Cyprus.
   Eight men were freed Friday and 98 women were released earlier
in the week.
   The clergymen, turned over to U.N. soldiers by the Turkish
Cypriots, went to the center of Nicosia where several hundred Greek
Cypriots welcomed them with patriotic songs.
   ``We will continue the struggle (for unity) but peacefully,''
the bishop said. ``I believe the Turkish Cypriots want to live in
peace with us.''
   The July 19 demonstration and detentions increased sectarian
tensions and delayed talks between Greek- and Turkish-Cypriot
leaders on reuniting the island.
   Cyprus has been partitioned since Turkey invaded the northern
third of the island after a short-lived coup by Greek Cypriots
wanting union with Greece.
   The Turkish Cypriots, who make up 17 percent of the population,
declared their own republic in 1983 but only Turkey has recognized
it.
   The clergymen were arrested by Turkish-Cypriot police who
entered a church on the green line dividing Nicosia as a memorial
service was being held for people killed or missing in the invasion.
   On July 22, the bishop and priest were each sentenced to three
days in jail and fined $200 on charges of llegally entering the
Turkish-Cypriot state.
   They refused to pay the fine and were ordered to serve an extra
10 days in prison.
   Turkish state radio said the two were released early because a
Greek-Cypriot businessman, who was not identified, paid their fines.
   Creek-Cypriot President George Vassiliou and Turkish-Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash had postponed a negotiating session set for
last Wednesday.
   They are expected to resume talks this week on a U.N. plan for
reuniting the island.
   The 2,300-member U.N. peacekeeping force patrols the 112-mile
buffer zone zigzagging across the island.
</TEXT>
