<FIRST>r a AM-SovereigntyCommission     07-30 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sovereignty Commission,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sovereignty Commission Records Show Owner of Black Newspaper Worked
for Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of Mississippi's leading black
newspaper in the 1960s worked for the segregationist Sovereignty
Commission, according to newly released records of the defunct
state agency.
   Percy Greene, who operated and edited the Jackson Advocate from
1938 until 1977, promoted the commission's views with telegrams,
letters, articles and speeches _ some prepared for him by
Commission Director Erle Johnston, the records state.
   A federal judge last week ordered the records of the commission,
which tried to thwart civil rights groups in the 1950s and 1960s,
be opened to the public. The judge barred the state from enforcing
a law making it a crime to disclose the records, which had been
sealed since 1977.
   The complete papers, in the archives of the McCain Graduate
Library at the University of Southern Mississippi in Hattiesburg,
were made available to The Clarion-Ledger on Friday in an agreement
with the attorney general. The papers cover Johnson's
administration from 1964 until 1968.
   Greene's efforts and payments made to him from 1964 until 1967
are outlined in commission records contained in the personal papers
of Gov. Paul B. Johnson Jr.
   A document dated Dec. 9, 1965, shows Johnston wrote remarks
about race relations in Mississippi for Greene to use during
national television news interviews while at a Los Angeles
newspaper rally.
   ``A lot has been said about the murder of three civil rights
workers in Neshoba County. There has been criticism that they have
never been tried in a state court for murder,'' reads the four-page
typewritten letter labeled ``Observations for Percy Greene.''
   Greene also was supposed to defend state officials who refused
to prosecute the case.
   ``The truth of the matter is that the Federal Bureau of
Investigation handled all of the interrogations and accumulated the
evidence,'' Johnston wrote in the document.
   Johnston also suggested that Greene criticize the U.S.
Department of Health, Education and Welfare for threatenting to cut
off funds to Mississippi public schools unless they desegregated.
   ``Such a decision would hurt the colored students more than the
white students,'' the letter reads.
   Greene founded the Advocate in 1938 and ran it until his death
in 1977.
   ``There was always suspicion that he was getting paid,'' said
Myrlie Evers, widow of Medgar Evers, the Mississippi NAACP field
secretary assassinated in 1963. ``I do recall, at one point, a
meeting held at our home where people were discussing Percy Greene
and what he was doing.''
   Charles Tisdale bought the paper in 1978 and is its publisher
and editor today.
   ``I have some of his correspondence to the Sovereignty
Commission. I'm not surprised at anything,'' Tisdale said Saturday
of Greene.
   The president of Mississippi's chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, Aaron Henry of
Clarksdale, was a member of the newspaper's board of directors
during Tisdale's tenure.
   He said Greene wasn't secretive about working for the
Sovereignty Commission.
   The commission obtained subscriptions of the Advocate for public
schools, Henry said Saturday.
   ``Percy had his problems with integration, but Percy was a
strong advocate of voting rights,'' Henry said.
   The present-day Advocate is ``completely different'' from
Greene's era, Henry said.
   ``It's really the voice of civil rights for this state,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
