<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Politics     07-30 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Politics,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputies Give Andreotti Government Final Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament's lower chamber gave Premier Giulio
Andreotti's government a vote of confidence on Sunday, formally
ending a two-month-long political crisis.
   The Chamber of Deputies approved the five-party coalition by a
vote of 371 to 200, with three abstentions. On Thursday, the Senate
voted 187 to 117, with one abstention, in favor of the government.
   Andreotti, premier for the sixth time, leads a coalition
dominated by his Christian Democrats, Italy's largest party. The
Socialists are the linchpin in the coalition. The other, much
smaller parties are the Republicans, Liberals and Social Democrats.
   The same five-party grouping has been the government formula for
most of the decade, as it was for the former premier, Christian
Democrat Ciriaco De Mita. His coalition government fell apart on
May 19 after persistent sniping by the Socialists, who are led by
De Mita's arch rival, Bettino Craxi.
   Members of the Chamber of Deputies from the five parties voted
in favor of Andreotti's coalition in the unusual Sunday session.
The Communists, Italy's second-largest party, led the dissent.
   Andreotti has said his coalition must act quickly to stem a
budget deficit and make Italy more efficient so it can compete in
the integrated European market, set for 1992.
   Among his priorities is increasing revenues, especially by
cracking down on rampant tax evasion.
