<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Moores     07-30 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Moores,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cecil Moores, Lottery Magnate, Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cecil Moores, a multimillionaire who operated the
Littlewoods lottery on soccer pools, died while on vacation in
Scotland, his family reported Sunday. He was 86.
   The family said he died Saturday but did not give the cause of
death.
   Moores was one of Britain's wealthiest men but lived modestly.
He was known to support charities in Liverpool's Merseyside
district where he was born.
   His brother, Sir John Moores, 83, founded the Littlewoods
lottery in 1924 with people betting on the results of weekly soccer
matches.
   Starting with 35 clients, the family built the business into
Britain's larges lottery-pools operation.
   It now has 5,000 employees and an annual income of about $800
million. The firm has said it will pay a top prize of $2.4 million
during the next soccer season.
   Cecil Moores took charge of the Littlewoods business in 1932
when his brother developed mail-order interests and later a chain
of stores.
   The brothers were the sons of a bricklayer and both started out
as printers.
   Cecil Moores was a soccer player in his youth and a lifelong
suporter of the Everton and Liverpool clubs in the English League's
first division.
   His wife died last year. He is survived by a son and daughter.
</TEXT>
