<FIRST>r f AM-Britain-Shenanigans Bjt   07-30 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Shenanigans, Bjt,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>London's Financial District Rocked Again By Stock Shenanigans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major stock scandal involving Britain's biggest
bank is rocking the City of London, prompting demands for tougher
policing of one of Europe's most important financial districts.
   The controversy, known as the Blue Arrow affair, has led to the
reluctant resignation of the chairman of the bank, National
Westminster PLC, and the abrupt departure of eight other people
from a variety of posts in the City.
   Chairman Lord Boardman protested that senior bank officials who
weren't directly involved have been unfairly singled out. But the
affair has damaged the bank's blue-chip reputation and perhaps its
expansion into investment banking.
   An official report severely criticizing the conduct of Natwest
officials in the 1987 sale of shares in Blue Arrow PLC, an
employment services agency, reflected a government move to crack
down on financial shenanigans in Britain.
   The furor has also raised questions about the adequacy of the
country's self-regulatory framework set up after the October 1986
deregulation of the nation's financial markets, called the Big Bang.
   ``British style of leave it to an old boy network was all right
when the old boys had standards,'' said legislator John Smith,
financial affairs spokesman for the opposition Labor Party. ``We're
in a world of global finance now where these things are swept
aside. We need tough enforcement.''
   The Blue Arrow affair follows what is known as the Guinness
scandal, in which the giant brewer Guinness PLC admitted that its
former management arranged for third parties to buy Guinness stock.
   The intention apparently was to inflate the share price and make
Guinness' ultimately successful, 1986 cash-and-stock offer for the
liquor company Distillers Co. more attractive than a rival bid.
   Seven men, including Guinness' deposed chairman, Ernest
Saunders, are awaiting trial on criminal charges.
   ``I think it's very clear to me standards in the City have
fallen dreadfully,'' Smith said at a recent gathering of the
Association of American Correspondents in London. ``We've now got a
whole series of these things.''
   The latest controversy grew out of Blue Arrow's audacious $1.3
billion acquisition of the much larger Manpower Inc. of the United
States in 1987, creating the world's largest employment services
agency.
   The official report, issued July 20 by the Department of Trade
and Industry after a seven-month probe, criticized Natwest
officials over the unsuccessful 837 million pound, or about $1.4
billion, sale of Blue Arrow shares to raise funds for that takeover.
   County Natwest Ltd., a securities unit of Natwest, kept shares
that didn't sell, failing to disclose a holding of more than 9.5
percent for three months. The trade department found misconduct and
a breach of British laws requiring timely disclosure of a stake of
more than 5 percent.
   London Metropolitan police's Serious Fraud Office is considering
whether criminal charges should be brought.
   The Securities Association, a self-regulatory body, says it is
investigating the conduct of four firms and 24 individuals in the
case. The Bank of England also is looking into the affair.
   Boardman, Natwest's 70-year-old chairman, and three other
directors resigned July 25 after an emergency meeting of the board
of directors. In addition, five other people have left their City
posts due to the scandal.
   The British press reported that the central bank has pressed for
``an appropriate response.''
   ``There obviously is an element of government crackdown on the
City in this,'' said Tim Clarke, a banking analyst with the London
investment firm Citicorp Scrimgeour Vickers. ``The government wants
to be seen as fairly hard on the City.''
   Boardman said he accepted ultimate responsibility for Natwest's
``serious failings.'' But he said he stepped down also because he
felt the report unjustly criticized the other three directors. He
himself was not singled out.
   The three were criticized for conduct that fell ``below that to
be expected from responsible senior executives.''
   ``Natwest has paid the price of inadequate supervision,'' the
Times of London wrote.
   Clarke said the affair underscores how difficult it is for banks
to move into the securities business, which was opened up to them
under Big Bang.
   It also underlines the difficulty in complying with the new,
complex regulations, he said. Investment firms also have complained
that they're expensive to follow.
   Smith, the Labor lawmaker, called for the establishment of a
government regulatory body modeled after the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   The government has transferred the responsibility for regulating
the financial services industry to a 17-member Securities and
Investments Board, a new, non-government watchdog body with
statutory powers. The board has approved five self-regulatory
organizations, including the Securities Association.
</TEXT>
