<FIRST>r f AM-Eastern-Shapiro     07-30 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Shapiro,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking Pilot's Father Seeking Disqualification of Eastern Examiner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney whose son is a striking Eastern
Airlines pilot contends that Eastern's court-appointed bankruptcy
examiner should be disqualified from the case because of an alleged
conflict of interest.
   The lawyer, Moreton Rolleston Jr., contends in a motion sent to
U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York that examiner David I. Shapiro
``cannot be completely impartial'' in Eastern's restructuring
because Shapiro's son works for a law firm representing the airline.
   Shapiro said Friday that his son, James, a second-year law
student at Georgetown University, is working for the Washington
office of Weil Gotshal &amp; Manges, handling environmental cases. The
New York-based firm is representing Eastern, but the younger
Shapiro is not handling any aspect of the case, his father said.
   ``I asked everybody if there was an objection. There were
none,'' Shapiro said. ``If there had been, James would have taken
another offer.''
   Rolleston, whose daughter-in-law is a flight attendant also on
strike against Eastern, said Shapiro ``must be like Caesar's wife,
that is, not only within the law but above suspicion.''
   Shapiro took offense at Rolleston's remarks.
   ``I view it as an attempt to attack me through my son. I don't
like it,'' Shapiro said.
   One of Shapiro's tasks as examiner is to investigate allegations
by the striking unions that Texas Air Corp., parent firm of the
airline, has stripped away Eastern assets to benefit the parent
company and sister carrier Continental Airlines.
   Shapiro said Friday he does not expect to report his findings
until September.
   Rolleston said he sent the motion last week to U.S. Bankruptcy
Court, but as of Friday it had not been filed with the clerk. The
attorney made copies of the motion available Friday to reporters.
   This is the second time Rolleston has intervened in the Eastern
case. In April, he petitioned the bankruptcy court to appoint a
trustee to run the airline during the reorganization, claiming that
since he had earned mileage in Eastern's frequent flier program he
was a party to the case. The request was not granted.
</TEXT>
