<FIRST>r f BC-PurinaPatent     07-30 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Purina Patent,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Against Ralston-Purina in Dog Chow Patent Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has eliminated Ralston
Purina Co.'s right to continue to enforce a patent used for the
production of Purina Dog Chow.
   U.S. District Judge Michael Mihm ruled Thursday that in 1975,
St. Louis-based Ralston Purina fraudulently obtained the patent for
the process used to make soy protein, a prime ingredient of Purina
Dog Chow, attorney Terry Grimm said Friday.
   Ralston Purina said it planned to appeal.
   The cereal and pet food maker had filed a lawsuit against A.E.
Staley Manufacturing for violating its patent.
   In ruling against Ralston Purina, Mihm cited arguments of the
attorneys for Decatur, Ill.-based Staley that Purina did not
disclose information in a Dutch publication that explained a
similar process developed by food processor Archer Daniels Midland
Co.
   Grimm, the attorney for Staley, said that while the ruling does
not revoke Ralston Purina's patent, it does mean that the company
will no longer be able to sue those who use the process.
   Grimm said those seeking patents at the U.S. Patent Office have
an obligation to report any information they may have about items
or processes for which they seek patent rights.
</TEXT>
