<FIRST>r f BC-GarfieldFood     07-30 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Garfield Food,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alpo To Enter Cat Food Market With Garfield</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Garfield is going to the dogs _ literally.
The feline cartoon character will help Alpo Petfoods Inc., better
known for its dog food, launch its new line of cat food.
   Alpo, the leading seller of premium canned dog food, will have
its Alpo brand cat food on supermarket shelves nationally in
November or early December, said Judi Kroeger, an Alpo spokeswoman.
   Garfield will proclaim on the label that the product is ``Good
Enough For Me.''
   The Allentown-based company, a division of the British
conglomerate Grand Metropolitan PLC, plans a multimillion-dollar
campaign to sell the product.
   ``We're really pleased that Jim Davis (Garfield's creator) has
worked with us since 1987 as the product was being developed,'' Ms.
Kroeger said. ``He's very particular about the items that Garfield
will endorse.''
   Ms. Kroeger said Alpo, which has researched and developed its
cat food for the last five years, believes it is financially
prudent to enter the market.
   ``The dog food market is limited in its business growth
potential because the dog population is declining, '' she said.
``The cat population is increasing, so cat food is one area that
companies can look to increase their business.''
   In 1983, Alpo bought the Tabby cat food company, which sells
only in the New England states. It followed by buying Blue Mountain
Co., which markets dog and cat food in the Northwest.
   Alpo commissioned a seven-member panel of veterinary and
nutrition experts to help develop the new cat food, Ms. Kroeger
said. The food was tested at Alpo and independent facilities.
   Its competition on the cat-food shelves will include Ralston
Purina Co.'s Purina brand and H.J. Heinz Co.'s 9-Lives.
   ``We know that these are strong brands and are not aiming to
overtake them by tomorrow afternoon,'' said Katherine A. Hillman,
Alpo's vice president for marketing. ``Garfield will certainly
assist in the initial trial, and the product's quality and
palatability will ensure strong repeat business.''
   In 1988, Alpo maintained its lead in the premium canned dog food
market by accounting for 28 percent of the estimated $920 million
market, according to Maxwell Consumer Report. The company also
advanced from fourth to second in dry dog food and dog snacks.
</TEXT>
