<FIRST>r f BC-Zell-Jepson     07-30 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Zell-Jepson,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Entreprenuer to Buy Jepson for $221.3 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Great American Management and Investment
Inc., a financial services, manufacturing and chemical company, has
agreed to buy the Jepson Corp. for $221.3 million, officials said.
   Jepson, based in suburban Elmhurst, said Thursday that Chairman
and Chief Executive Robert S. Jepson Jr. and his family agreed to
sell their 12.7 million shares to a subsidiary of Great American,
headed by entrepreneur Sam Zell.
   The Jepson family shares represent 69.1 percent of the total,
and Zell said he would make a $12-a-share cash tender offer for the
other 5.7 million shares.
   Chicago-based Great American was attracted to ``the collection
of growing businesses that we felt could be improved upon and added
to,'' Zell said.
   Jepson has three main divisions: consumer products, such as
Hedstrom toys; commercial products, including Jepson Burns
commercial aircraft seats; and industrial products.
   Last summer, Robert Jepson said the company might seek a seller
to maximize shareholder value. The company went public in 1987,
with the stock selling initially at $13 a share, but has traded
considerably below that most of the time since.
   Jepson stock closed up 12{ cents at $11.75 Friday on the New
York Stock Exchange.
