<FIRST>r f BC-EnginePlant     07-30 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Engine Plant,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>Announcement Expected on Engine Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Australian company will build a $250
million plant in Michigan to make a three-cylinder engine that
could revolutionize the auto industry, an official said.
   Announcement of the plant by Gov. James Blanchard is expected
Wednesday, state Commerce Department spokesman Dale Arnold said
Friday. The plant would employ 700 workers.
   The two-stroke engine, which is lighter, more powerful and
cleaner burning than conventional engines, was invented by Ralph
Sarich. His company, Orbital Engine Co. in Perth, Australia, has
signed licensing agreements with Ford Motor Co. and General Motors
Corp.
   The engine's pistons require two strokes to burn fuel instead of
the usual four.
   ``It is my understanding that the automakers are extremely
serious about this engine,'' said Robert Brooks, an industry
consultant in Waukegan, Ill.
</TEXT>
