<FIRST>r f BC-TimkenLayoffs     07-30 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Timken Layoffs,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steelmaker Notifies 900 Workers of Indefinite Layoffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Notices have been distributed to 900
employees at two Timken Co. steel plants advising them that they
face indefinite layoffs beginning Sept. 30.
   The notices came two weeks after the Canton-based steelmaker
confirmed that 200 layoffs were planned for late July and August.
   Company spokesman James Mulder said a ``softening demand for
steel'' was the reason for the layoffs at the two plants in this
northeastern Ohio city. Friday's notices comply with a federal law
requiring 60-day notifications of layoffs, he said.
   Jack Nichelson, president of the United Steelworkers of America
Local 1123, said he was surprised by the layoffs.
   ``Normally, the company lays people off because of lack of work.
But we have had no indication that there has been a drop in steel
orders,'' Nichelson said.
   Nichelson said the company's ball bearings operations had been
busier recently than its steel operation, with many bearing
employees working six days a week.
