<FIRST>r f BC-TGIFriday's     07-30 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-TGI Friday's,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minnesota Company To Acquire TGI Friday's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TGI Friday's, a casual restaurant chain, will
become a private company in a merger with Carlson Hospitality Group
Inc. of Minnesota, the parent company of the Radisson hotel chain,
officials said.
   Since 1975, Carlson has been increasing its stake in
Dallas-based TGI Friday's and owned 80 percent of the restaurant
chain when the merger agreement was announced Friday. It will pay
about $52 million, or $14.87{ a share, for the remaining
outstanding shares.
   The deal must be approved by shareholders. It is supported by
TGI Friday's Chairman Curtis Carlson.
   In May, the company offered $14.50 a share, but several
shareholders filed lawsuits challenging the bid.
   TGI Friday's operates, franchises or licenses more than 150
Friday's and Dalts restaurants in the United States, Great Britain
and Mexico.
   No changes are planned in the colorful restaurants, many of
which are feature an early 20th century Americana motif. The
chain's headquarters will remain in Dallas, officials said.
   TGI Friday's went public in 1983, selling 25 percent of its
stock.
   Thomas Polski, a Carlson Hospitality Group spokesman, would not
discuss reasons for the buyout.
   Carlson Hospitality is the hotel and restaurant subsidiary of
Carlson Cos., a diversified travel industry corporation that is
privately held.
</TEXT>
